==Criticism==
Comedy Central has been a frequent target of criticism from the conservative group [[Parents Television Council]], which accuses them of [[bigotry]] and [[blasphemy]],<ref>{{cite web | last = Bozell | first = L. Brent III | authorlink = L. Brent Bozell III | title = Comedy Central's War on Christmas | work = [[CNS News]] | publisher = [[Creators Syndicate]] | date = December 22, 2005 | url = http://www.cnsnews.com/bozellcolumn/archive/2005/col20051222.asp | accessdate = 2007-08-01 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080201043432/http://www.cnsnews.com/bozellcolumn/archive/2005/col20051222.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = February 1, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Comedy Central Shows God in One-Night Stand | publisher = [[Parents Television Council]] | date = March 9, 2007 | url = http://www.parentstv.org/PTC/publications/release/2007/0309.asp | accessdate = 2007-08-01 }}</ref> especially within the programs ''[[South Park]]'', ''[[The Sarah Silverman Program]]'', ''[[Halfway Home (TV series)|Halfway Home]]'', and the annual "Roast" special.<ref>{{cite web | last = Bozell | first = L. Brent III | authorlink = L. Brent Bozell III | title = Roasting the Final Frontier | work = [[Media Research Center|MRC.org]] | publisher = [[Creators Syndicate]] | date =  August 24, 2006 | url = http://www.mrc.org/BozellColumns/entertainmentcolumn/2006/col20060824.asp | accessdate = 2007-08-01 }}</ref> The PTC has used their criticisms against Comedy Central for their support of the [[Family and Consumer Choice Act of 2007]], which would allow American [[cable television in the United States|cable television]] subscribers to choose which channels they subscribe to and impose the same decency standards that are already in place on broadcast TV,<ref>{{cite web | last = Isett | first = Dan | authorlink = Parents_Television_Council#Leadership | title = Remarks Presented by Dan Isett of the PTC at the News Conference Regarding the "Family and Consumer Choice Act of 2007" | publisher = [[Parents Television Council]] | date = June 14, 2007 | url = http://www.parentstv.org/ptc/publications/news/cablebill-danisett.asp | accessdate = 2007-08-01 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070930200903/http://www.parentstv.org/ptc/publications/news/cablebill-danisett.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref> and to persuade advertisers to stop advertising on the channel.<ref>{{cite web | last = Bozell | first = L. Brent III | authorlink = L. Brent Bozell III | title = Letter to Advertisers Concerning their Sponsorship of the August 16th Roast of Pamela Anderson on Comedy Central | publisher = [[Parents Television Council]] | date = September 6, 2005 | url = http://www.parentstv.org/PTC/advertisers/letters/Various_Roast_090605.htm | accessdate = 2007-08-01 }}</ref> PTC founder and former president [[L. Brent Bozell III]] has called the channel unfunny, claiming the channel has managed "to reach the top of its field in spite of – or, better put, because of – the network's sheer lack of comedic talent" by its "extensive reliance on shocking or disgusting humor".<ref>{{cite web | last = Bozell | first = L. Brent III | authorlink = L. Brent Bozell III | title = The Arrested Adolescent's Channel | work = [[CNS News]] | publisher = [[Creators Syndicate]] | date = March 24, 2006 | url = http://www.cnsnews.com/bozellcolumn/archive/2006/col20060324.asp | accessdate = 2007-08-01 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070611135632/http://www.cnsnews.com/bozellcolumn/archive/2006/col20060324.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = June 11, 2007}}</ref> The PTC attacked the channel<ref>[http://www.parentstv.org/ptc/letters/main.asp#4 Parents Television Council – Letters to the Editor – Offensive Ads]{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> for airing advertisements for "[[Girls Gone Wild (franchise)|Girls Gone Wild]]". The channel airs the least [[censorship|censored]] version of the film ''[[Not Another Teen Movie]]'', as well as [[cut (censorship)|uncut]] versions of films such as ''[[Coming to America]]'', ''[[Dogma (film)|Dogma]]'' and ''[[Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back]]''.

On November 5, 2007, an open letter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videosift.com/talk/An-Open-Letter-to-Comedy-Central-and-Viacom |title=VideoSifts open letter to Comedy Central and Viacom |publisher=Videosift.com |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref> was written by [[VideoSift]] to protesting the blocking of Comedy Central's embedded video content for non-U.S. based viewers.

On April 21, 2010, Comedy Central [[201 (South Park)#Censorship|censored]] the ''[[South Park]]'' episode, "[[201 (South Park)|201]]", in response to a [[death threat]] issued by users of a [[Revolution Muslim|radical Muslim website]] over the episode's planned depiction of the [[Prophets of Islam|Islamic prophet]] [[Muhammad]], which led several newspaper columnists to condemn the network's actions as tantamount to abetting terrorism. As a result, "201" and [[200 (South Park)|the episode that preceded it]] were heavily edited and not shown in repeats.

